Homework 2

In this homework, we wish to investigate Abouir, et al., (2022) to assess the validity of several claims. First of all, we need to select the observations for different analysis.

library(idar)
data(codex)

# Cmax
Cmax_men = codex$cmax[codex$gender == 0]
Cmax_women = codex$cmax[codex$gender == 1]
Cmax_non_obese = codex$cmax[codex$obese == 0]
Cmax_obese = codex$cmax[codex$obese == 1]

# Tmax
Tmax_men = codex$tmax[codex$gender == 0]
Tmax_women = codex$tmax[codex$gender == 1]
Tmax_non_obese = codex$tmax[codex$obese == 0]
Tmax_obese = codex$tmax[codex$obese == 1]

# AUC
AUC_men = codex$auc[codex$gender == 0]
AUC_women = codex$auc[codex$gender == 1]
AUC_non_obese = codex$auc[codex$obese == 0]
AUC_obese = codex$auc[codex$obese == 1]

Question 1: Difference between groups for \(C_{\max}\)

Lets have a look at the empirical distributions:

par(mfrow = c(1, 2))
boxplot_w_points(Cmax_women, Cmax_men, names = c("Women", "Men"), ylab = "Cmax (ng/ml)")
boxplot_w_points(Cmax_obese, Cmax_non_obese, names = c("Obese", "Non-obese"), ylab = "Cmax (ng/ml)")

Based on these graphs, it is reasonable to believe that some outliers are present. Thus, we select Wilcoxon test to compare the means of the different groups.

wilcox.test(Cmax_men, Cmax_women, alternative = "less")
## 
##  Wilcoxon rank sum exact test
## 
## data:  Cmax_men and Cmax_women
## W = 43, p-value = 0.001661
## alternative hypothesis: true location shift is less than 0
wilcox.test(Cmax_obese, Cmax_non_obese, alternative = "less")
## 
##  Wilcoxon rank sum exact test
## 
## data:  Cmax_obese and Cmax_non_obese
## W = 85, p-value = 0.1335
## alternative hypothesis: true location shift is less than 0

From the result we can see that the p-value = 0.001661 in the first test is smaller than 0.05, which indicates there are some evidence against the null hypotheses in favor of the alternative. Therefore, at the 95% confidence level, we reject the null and accept the alternative hypothesis that the mean of the variable cmax in group of women is smaller than that of the group men. However, for the second test, there isnt enough an evidence to reject the null hypothesis which we assert that the means for the variable cmax are the same between the groups obese and non_obese. Interestingly, different conclusions would be obtained if we were use a (Welch) t-test:

t.test(Cmax_men, Cmax_women, alternative = "less")
## 
##  Welch Two Sample t-test
## 
## data:  Cmax_men and Cmax_women
## t = -2.9365, df = 19.255, p-value = 0.004194
## alternative hypothesis: true difference in means is less than 0
## 95 percent confidence interval:
##       -Inf -42.53625
## sample estimates:
## mean of x mean of y 
##  122.8219  226.1786
t.test(Cmax_obese, Cmax_non_obese, alternative = "less")
## 
##  Welch Two Sample t-test
## 
## data:  Cmax_obese and Cmax_non_obese
## t = -1.7488, df = 21.493, p-value = 0.0473
## alternative hypothesis: true difference in means is less than 0
## 95 percent confidence interval:
##       -Inf -1.107418
## sample estimates:
## mean of x mean of y 
##  138.6667  203.4433

Indeed, we obtain a p-value smaller than \(\alpha = 0.05\) for the second test leading to a different conclusion.

Question 2: Difference between groups for \(T_{\max}\)

We proceed similarly for the second question:

par(mfrow = c(1, 2))
boxplot_w_points(Tmax_women, Tmax_men, names = c("Women", "Men"), ylab = "Tmax (h)")
boxplot_w_points(Tmax_obese, Tmax_non_obese, names = c("Obese", "Non-obese"), ylab = "Tmax (h)")

Based on these graphs, we also select Wilcoxon test and obtain the p-values as follows:

wilcox.test(Tmax_women, Tmax_men, alternative = "less")
## Warning in wilcox.test.default(Tmax_women, Tmax_men, alternative = "less"):
## cannot compute exact p-value with ties
## 
##  Wilcoxon rank sum test with continuity correction
## 
## data:  Tmax_women and Tmax_men
## W = 76, p-value = 0.06983
## alternative hypothesis: true location shift is less than 0
wilcox.test(Tmax_obese, Tmax_non_obese, alternative = "less")
## Warning in wilcox.test.default(Tmax_obese, Tmax_non_obese, alternative =
## "less"): cannot compute exact p-value with ties
## 
##  Wilcoxon rank sum test with continuity correction
## 
## data:  Tmax_obese and Tmax_non_obese
## W = 111.5, p-value = 0.4917
## alternative hypothesis: true location shift is less than 0

Thus, we fail the reject the null hypothesis at the 95% confidence level for both tests.

Question 3: Difference between groups for AUC

We proceed similarly for the last question:

par(mfrow = c(1, 2))
boxplot_w_points(AUC_women, AUC_men, names = c("Women", "Men"), ylab = "AUC (ng.h/ml)")
boxplot_w_points(AUC_obese, AUC_non_obese, names = c("Obese", "Non-obese"), ylab = "AUC (ng.h/ml)")

We obtain the p-values are follows:

wilcox.test(AUC_men, AUC_women, alternative = "less")
## 
##  Wilcoxon rank sum exact test
## 
## data:  AUC_men and AUC_women
## W = 36, p-value = 0.0005263
## alternative hypothesis: true location shift is less than 0
wilcox.test(AUC_obese, AUC_non_obese, alternative = "less")
## 
##  Wilcoxon rank sum exact test
## 
## data:  AUC_obese and AUC_non_obese
## W = 78, p-value = 0.08034
## alternative hypothesis: true location shift is less than 0

Therefore, at the 95% confidence level, we reject the null hypothesis for the test and accept the alternative hypothesis stating that the mean of the variable auc in group of women is smaller than that of the group men. However, for the second test, there isnt enough an evidence (at the 95% confidence level) to reject the null hypothesis which we assert that the means for the variable auc are the same between the groups obese and non_obese.
